Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – US policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in just one month.
For ten years, never had so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, although their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded following the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were mainly felt during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not outright inflammatory), has undoubtedly benefited from this.
Some politicians are even speaking of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the attack in San Bernardino, California, last December.
But candidates for president, as well as certain media outlets, who adhere to the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated its proportions.
To put terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should, like others, keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists are more concerned with capturing attention and dominating political headlines than with the actual number of their victims.
ISIS takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric beheadings posted on social media are meant to destabilize and shock – and thus to monopolize attention.
Overexaggerating their consequences and making big headlines with each terrorist act is playing the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the greatest threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills much less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
The Americans are much more likely to die in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from a domestic appliance accident (one in 1.5 million), hit by a deer or elk crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year texting while driving or talking on their mobile phones.
This is several hundred times the number who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than workplace shootings or mass shootings at universities or schools.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a wave of terrorism.
In the early 20th century, the anarchist movement killed several heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Armed Revolutionary Fraction, stemming from the "autonomous" left, hijacked planes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon cloaked in religious garb.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorism that preceded it was.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke citizens of a state enough to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain an advantage.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda succeeded in drawing Americans to Afghanistan.
ISIS was born in the ruins of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, you need smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of attraction and persuasion.
Influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery who the irreducibles seek to recruit.
This is why the attention paid to the narrative of events and how US actions are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precise aerial strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all at risk.
Reason why the current presidential election candidates' anti-Islam stance is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and law enforcement agencies, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important element of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap laid by the terrorists.
Do not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and bullies unfold.
If we leave them our grand stage of public discourse, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
